<DOC><DOCNO> AP890829-0135 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2011EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-Strike     08-29 0417</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-Strike,0434</SECOND><HEAD>Government Arrests Thousands in Sweep to Block Strike</HEAD><BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The government reportedly arrested 5,000political workers Tuesday and asked others to stay in officesovernight to prevent a nationwide strike to demand the resignationof Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.   Four major opposition parties set the general strike forWednesday in their latest attempt to focus attention on theircharges of government corruption.   United News of India news agency said as many as 5,000 politicalworkers were arrested across the country Tuesday. There were nodetails on any charges.   The opposition has said that all businesses should be closed andpublic transportation, except for essential services, should come toa halt during the strike. The strike was intended as a show ofstrength before parliamentry elections later this year.   The government also asked thousands of its employees to stay intheir offices overnight so they could report for duty Wednesday.   Officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said thegovernment was paying to provide food and bedrolls for theemployees. They were allowed to bring children into offices, theofficials said.   Senior government executives were given rooms in luxury hotelsnear their offices, they said.   No official announcement was made about how many employees wereinvolved. Government employees in New Delhi said thousands of peoplewere being asked to stay on.   United News of India quoted an unidentified government spokesmanas saying officials absent from work Wednesday would lose a day'ssalary.   The government planned to provide full security to all Indianswho wish to work, he was quoted as saying. Trains, state-ownedbuses, and air services would function normally, he reportedly said.   The opposition has repeatedly accused the government ofcorruption in past weeks.   Last month, 106 opposition members in Parliament demanded thatGandhi resign, saying a July government audit of an arms deal showedthat senior officials received kickbacks.   When Gandhi refused, the opposition members resigned in a raredisplay of solidarity.   The opposition charge relates to a $1.4 billion deal for purchaseof artillery guns from AB Bofors of Sweden. Opposition politicianssay the Swedish company paid kickbacks amounting to $50 million togovernment officials and members of Gandhi's Congress Party.   No proof has been offered, and the government has deniedwrongdoing.   The new elections must be held sometime before the end of theyear. In the last general elections in 1985, the Congress Party won415 of 544 seats in Parliament.</TEXT></DOC>